<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910109-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>910109-0055.</DOCID><HL>   Big V Supermarkets Inc.   Is Sold by Investor Group</HL><DATE>01/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   Z.CSH</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- The investor group that bought out Big VSupermarkets Inc. three years ago for $175 million has cashedout for $200 million in a case -- getting rarer these days --of a leveraged buy-out that held up well.   The group, led by affiliates of CS First Boston Inc. andMetropolitan Life Insurance Co., said it sold the supermarketchain to Big V Holding Corp., which was formed by the Bostoninvestment firm Thomas H. Lee Co. and three affiliates. BigV, based in Florida, N.Y., consists of 27 Shop-Ritesupermarkets located primarily in New York state.</LP><TEXT>   While an increasing number of companies taken private indebt-financed leveraged buy-outs haven't fared well, CS FirstBoston made a significant return on its investment, saidAndrew R. Taussig, managing director of First Boston Corp.,CS First Boston's investment-banking unit. &quot;The company'soperating performance met all of our expectations, and ourreturns exceeded our investment goals,&quot; he said.   Big V, of Florida, N.Y., was acquired in November 1987.Mr. Taussig declined to say how much First Boston made on thesale, but he said it was &quot;significantly more than $25million,&quot; the difference between the acquisition and saleprices.   Mr. Taussig attributes the success of the buy-out to astrategy that included the sale of some Big V real estate,the closing of about six unprofitable stores, the upgradingof others and the leadership of its managers.</TEXT></DOC>